@@.use
* 1 tablespoon olive oil
* 1 onion, sliced
* kosher salt
* 8 bone-in, skin on chicken thighs or drumsticks or a combination of both
* 2 teaspoons turmeric
* 2 teaspoons curry powder
* 1 to 3 tablespoons Thai red curry paste (see notes above)
* 3 to 4 plum tomatoes, chopped
* 1 can unsweetened coconut milk
* 1 tablespoon fish sauce
* 2 teaspoons brown sugar
* 1/2 cup cilantro, roughly chopped, or more or less to taste
* 3 to 5 ounces spinach, optional
@@

@@.prep
# Heat oven to 400ºF.
# In a large sauté pan over hight heat, heat 1 tablespoon of olive oil. Add the onions and a pinch of salt, and immediately turn the heat to medium-low. Stir every so often, and cook until the onions soften and begin browning at the edges, about 5 minutes.
# Meanwhile, place the chicken in a large bowl and season all over with kosher salt. Use 1 teaspoon per pound.
# Add the curry powder, turmeric, and Thai red curry paste to the onions, and stir until onions are coated  in the spices, about a minute. Add the tomatoes, and stir until they just begin to soften, about a minute. Add the can of coconut milk. Fill up the empty can of coconut milk with water and add to the pan. Add the fish sauce and brown sugar and bring to a simmer. (Note: A number of people have had issues with this being too liquidy, so I’ve reduced the amount of water from 2 empty cans to one… hope this solves the issues.).  
# Add the chicken pieces and turn to coat. Transfer pan to the oven uncovered and cook for 1 hour or until the liquid has reduced considerably, the chicken skin is brown, and the meat is falling off the bone. If the liquid has reduced too much, add more by the quarter cup. Note: If you make this ahead, you may need to add more water upon reheating. 
# Add cilantro and stir. Add spinach, if using, and stir. Spoon rice into bowls. Top with chicken and sauce, and serve immediately.
@@


@@.notes
* If your chicken thighs or drumsticks are particularly fatty, trim the excess fat. This will prevent your sauce from being too fatty in the end.
* Thai red curry paste. Maesri is the brand I buy at the Asian market. You can find it online, too. I use half a tin for this recipe (which is about 3 tablespoons), which makes it quite spicy but not outrageous. If you are sensitive to heat, start with a tablespoon and adjust the sauce with more at the end.
@@






@@.use
* 2 tbsp coconut oil or olive oil
* 1 medium yellow onion, chopped
* 4 garlic cloves, minced
* 2-3 tbsp Thai red curry paste
* 2 tsp ground coriander
* 1 tsp ground cumin
* 1/4 tsp sea salt
* 1/4 tsp crushed red pepper flakes
* 2 lb butternut squash, peeled, seeded, cut into 1/2 inch pieces, approx 3 cups
* 4 cups vegetable broth
* 1 tbsp lime juice
* 1/4 cup fresh cilantro, chopped, garnish
@@

@@.prep
# In Dutch oven, heat oil over medium heat. Add onion, garlic, curry paste, coriander, cumin , salt, red pepper flakes. Cook until onion is translucent, approx 5 minutes
# Add butternut squash and cook for 1 minute. Add broth, bringing to a boil, then reducing and simmering until squash is soft, approx 15-20 minutes
# Remove soup from heat and let cool slightly. Transfer to blender in batches and blend until smooth.
# Sitr lime juice into blended soup and top with cilantro
@@






* Three Bean Salad
* PREP TIME
* 10 mins
* TOTAL TIME
* 10 mins
* SERVINGS
* 4 to 8 servings
* Prep the onion first. Soak the chopped onion in a small bowl of water to take the edge off the onion while you prep the other ingredients.
* Ingredients
* For the salad:
* 
* 1 (15-ounce) can cannellini beans, rinsed and drained
* 1 (15-ounce) can kidney beans, rinsed and drained
* 1 (15-ounce) can garbanzo beans, rinsed and drained
* 1/2 red onion, finely chopped (about 3/4 cup), soaked in water to take the edge off the onion
* 2 celery stalks, finely chopped (about 1 cup)
* 1 cup loosely packed, fresh, finely chopped flat-leaf parsley
* 1 teaspoon fresh finely chopped rosemary
* For the dressing:
* 
* 1/3 cup apple cider vinegar
* 1/4 cup granulated sugar (more or less to taste)
* 3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
* 1 1/2 teaspoons salt
* 1/4 teaspoon black pepper












@@.use
* 2½ pounds roma tomatoes, halved
* ¼ cup extra-virgin olive oil, divided
* 1 medium yellow onion, chopped
* ⅓ cup chopped carrots
* 4 garlic cloves, chopped
* 3 cups vegetable broth
* 1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar
* 1 teaspoon thyme leaves
* 1 loose-packed cup basil leaves, more for garnish
* Sea salt and freshly ground black pepper
@@

@@.prep
# Preheat the oven to 350°F and line a large baking sheet with parchment paper. Place the tomatoes cut-side up on the baking sheet, drizzle with 2 tablespoons of the olive oil, and sprinkle with salt and pepper. Roast for 1 hour or until the edges just start to shrivel and the insides are still juicy.
# Heat the remaining 2 tablespoons of olive oil in a large pot over medium heat. Add the onions, carrots, garlic, and ½ teaspoon salt and cook until soft, about 8 minutes. Stir in the tomatoes, vegetable broth, vinegar, and thyme leaves and simmer for 20 minutes.
# Let cool slightly and pour the soup into a blender, working in batches if necessary. Blend until smooth. Add the basil and pulse until combined.
# Garnish the soup with basil leaves and serve with crusty bread.
@@


@@.notes
* Roma tomatoes – Just like in my homemade salsa recipe, the tomato variety you use here matters. If you can’t find roma tomatoes, substitute another variety of small plum tomatoes. Larger heirloom or salad tomatoes are too watery for this recipe.
* Use fresh basil – You can’t make tomato basil soup without it! I blend in the basil right at the end so that it keeps its fresh flavor and flecks the soup with green.
@@

font-weight: 500; font-style: normal; text-transform: none;"><h3 class="wprm-recipe-header wprm-recipe-instructions-header wprm-block-text-normal" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-family: Lora, serif; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.2; margin: 20px 0px 8px; color: rgb(244, 121, 108); font-size: 18px; font-style: normal; text-transform: none; clear: none; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: 0px; padding: 0px;">Instructions</h3><div class="wprm-recipe-instruction-group" style="box-sizing: border-box;"><ul class="wprm-recipe-instructions" style="box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 0px 32px; margin-block-start: 0px; margin-block-end: 0px; padding-inline-start: 0px;"><li id="wprm-recipe-22508-step-0-0" class="wprm-recipe-instruction" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 1em; margin: 0px 0px 4px; padding: 0px; list-style-position: outside; position: relative; line-height: 1.6; counter-increment: instruction-counter 1; list-style-type: decimal;"><div class="wprm-recipe-instruction-text" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 1em;">Mix Minted Yoghurt Sauce ingredients in a bowl. Set aside for 20 + minutes.</div></li><li id="wprm-recipe-22508-step-0-1" class="wprm-recipe-instruction" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 1em; margin: 0px 0px 4px; padding: 0px; list-style-position: outside; position: relative; line-height: 1.6; counter-increment: instruction-counter 1; list-style-type: decimal;"><div class="wprm-recipe-instruction-text" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 1em;">Place Meatball ingredients EXCEPT OIL in a bowl. Mix well.</div></li><li id="wprm-recipe-22508-step-0-2" class="wprm-recipe-instruction" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 1em; margin: 0px 0px 4px; padding: 0px; list-style-position: outside; position: relative; line-height: 1.6; counter-increment: instruction-counter 1; list-style-type: decimal;"><div class="wprm-recipe-instruction-text" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 1em;"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: block;">Measure out 1 heaped tablespoon, then roll into balls. Repeat with remaining mixture - should have 22 - 24 meatballs.</span></div></li><li id="wprm-recipe-22508-step-0-3" class="wprm-recipe-instruction" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 1em; margin: 0px 0px 4px; padding: 0px; list-style-position: outside; position: relative; line-height: 1.6; counter-increment: instruction-counter 1; list-style-type: decimal;"><div class="wprm-recipe-instruction-text" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 1em;">Heat oil in a skillet over medium heat. Add half the meatballs and cook, turning to brown all over, for 8 minutes, or until cooked through. Transfer to plate, then cook the remaining meatballs.</div></li><li id="wprm-recipe-22508-step-0-4" class="wprm-recipe-instruction" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 1em; margin: 0px 0px 4px; padding: 0px; list-style-position: outside; position: relative; line-height: 1.6; counter-increment: instruction-counter 1; list-style-type: decimal;"><div class="wprm-recipe-instruction-text" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 1em;"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: block;">OVEN OPTION instead of stove: Preheat at 200C/390F. Spray with oil then bake for 20 minutes until browned. Sometimes I put them on a rack to keep them round (put the rack on a tray).</span></div></li><li id="wprm-recipe-22508-step-0-5" class="wprm-recipe-instruction" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 1em; margin: 0px 0px 4px; padding: 0px; list-style-position: outside; position: relative; line-height: 1.6; counter-increment: instruction-counter 1; list-style-type: decimal;"><div class="wprm-recipe-instruction-text" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 1em;">Cut pita pockets in half, warm for 10 seconds in the microwave, then pry it open. Stuff with Salad, then meatballs. Finish with Yoghurt Sauce and more fresh mint and coriander if desired.</div></li></ul></div></div><div class="wprm-recipe-notes-container wprm-block-text-normal" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 500; font-style: normal; text-transform: none; margin: 24px -16px; background: rgb(255, 255, 255); padding: 16px;"><h3 class="wprm-recipe-header wprm-recipe-notes-header wprm-block-text-normal" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-family: Lora, serif; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.2; margin: 0px 0px 8px; color: rgb(244, 121, 108); font-size: 18px; font-style: normal; text-transform: none; clear: none; font-variant: normal; letter-spacing: 0px; padding: 0px;"><i class="fas fa-pencil" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-style: italic;"></i>Recipe Notes:</h3><div class="wprm-recipe-notes" style="box-sizing: border-box;"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: block;">1. This recipe is also terrific with beef, and very good with chicken and turkey. No recipe adjustments. If baking the chicken or turkey meatballs, spray VERY well with oil!</span><div class="wprm-spacer" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 0px; line-height: 0; width: 578px; height: 10px; display: block !important; background: 0px 0px !important;"></div><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: block;"><strong style="box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;">2. Suggested sides if you opt out of the pita pockets:</strong> The<span> </span><a href="https://www.recipetineats.com/shredded-red-cabbage-carrot-mint-salad/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; color: rgb(244, 121, 108); transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;">Shredded Red Cabbage, Carrot and Mint Salad</a><span> </span>is great as a side salad as well, this<span> </span><a href="https://www.recipetineats.com/middle-eastern-spiced-chickpea-salad/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; color: rgb(244, 121, 108); transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;">Middle Eastern chopped salad</a><span> </span>(skip the chickpeas),<span> </span><a href="https://www.recipetineats.com/israeli-couscous-salad/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; color: rgb(244, 121, 108); transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;">Israeli Couscous Salad</a>,<span> </span><a href="https://www.recipetineats.com/pico-de-gallo-authentic/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; color: rgb(244, 121, 108); transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;">Pico de Gallo</a><span> </span>(I know it's Mexican but the flavours are terrific paired with Middle Eastern), just the rice in this baked<span> </span><a href="https://www.recipetineats.com/one-skillet-baked-chicken-shawarma-and-rice-pilaf/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; color: rgb(244, 121, 108); transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;">Chicken &amp; Rice<span> </span></a>recipe,<span> </span><a href="https://www.recipetineats.com/chargrilled-vegetable-platter/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; color: rgb(244, 121, 108); transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;">Chargrilled Vegetables</a>,<span> </span><a href="https://www.recipetineats.com/lemon-rice-pilaf/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; color: rgb(244, 121, 108); transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;">Lemon Pilaf</a><span> </span>(fab pairing!),<span> </span><a href="https://www.recipetineats.com/curried-rice-basmati-rice-recipe/" style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; color: rgb(244, 121, 108); transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;">Curried Basmati Rice Pilaf</a>, this<span> </span><a href="https://www.recipetineats.com/chickpea-rice-pilaf/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; color: rgb(244, 121, 108); transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;">Chickpea Rice Pilaf</a>,<span> </span><a href="https://www.recipetineats.com/fattoush-with-crunchy-flatbread-ribbons/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; color: rgb(244, 121, 108); transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;">Fattoush</a>. Because the meatballs are heavily spiced, opt for sides with fresh flavours.</span><div class="wprm-spacer" style="box-sizing: border-box; font-size: 0px; line-height: 0; width: 578px; height: 10px; display: block !important; background: 0px 0px !important;"></div><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: block;">3. Nutrition for meatballs and yoghurt sauce, assuming all the sauce is consumed which it may not be. Also assumes no fat is drained off but I usually discard about 1 tbsp at the end of cooking so the calories will be lower than stated.</span></div></div></div>

@@.use
* 12 oz whole wheat thin spaghetti (or any noodle you like)
*1 cup shredded purple cabbage
*1 cup carrot ribbons
*1 cup baby spinach
*1.5 cups bell pepper strips
*1 cup shelled cooked edamame
*1/2 cup cilantro
*peanut sauce:
* 1/2 cup peanut butter
* 2 tsp sriracha
* 4 tbsp soy sauce
* 3 tbsp rice vinegar
* 1/4 cup water
* 1 tbsp maple syrup
* 1 tbsp toasted sesame oil
* 1 tsp garlic
*1 tsp ginger
@@

@@.prep
# cook noods, 
#prep veggies, 
#mix sauce ingredients together 
#combine!
@@

@@.notes
https://www.instagram.com/p/CeCZ0GsphjD/
@@












@@.use

* 1 tbsp. olive oil
* 4 eggs (well beaten)
* 1 tbsp butter (margarine)
* Salt and pepper (to taste)
* 1 red (or yellow bell pepper, chopped small)
* 1 green bell pepper (chopped small)
* Optional: 1/2 tsp. garlic powder
* Optional: 1/2 onion (diced) 
@@

# First, crack your eggs into a small and beat them together well with a fork. Some people suggest adding a teaspoon or two of water for a fluffier omelet, though, with all those bell peppers, this isn't the fluffiest of omelets anyways.
# Sautee the diced onion in olive oil for 3 to 5 minutes. Add the red or yellow and green chopped bell peppers, and cook for another minute or two just until the bell peppers are lightly tender.
# Add the onions and peppers to the beaten eggs and combine well.
# In a large non-stick skillet or frying pan, heat the butter or margarine. Give the pan a quick tilt, to make sure the butter coats the entire bottom of the pan. Next, pour in the egg mixture and sprinkle it all with a dash of salt and pepper and the garlic powder. Sea salt or kosher salt and fresh ground black pepper is always the best choice for the best quality flavor. 
# Tilt the pan as your omelet starts to cook in order to allow the uncooked parts in the middle to come out to edges of the pan and cook quicker and more evenly.
# Allow your vegetable omelet to cook until the bottom of the eggs are lightly golden brown, then, using a rubber spatula, gently fold your omelet in half and allow it all to cook for a few more minutes.








@@.use


* 2 packages crescent rolls
* 2 (8 ounce) packages cream cheese softened
* 1 cup mayonnaise
* 1 packet dry Ranch dressing mix
* 1 cup chopped broccoli
* 1 cup chopped cauliflower
* 1 cup chopped or shredded carrots
* 1 cup shredded cheddar cheese
* 1/4 cup each additional chopped vegetables such as bell pepper, tomato, scallions, or black olives

@@

@@.prep
# Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Line a 11-inch by 17-inch or larger baking sheet with parchment paper or aluminum foil.
# Unroll crescent roll triangles and arrange into rectangles to from a crust, pressing the seams together.
# Bake the crust according to the package instructions, about 12 to 15 minutes or until golden brown. Remove from oven and cool completely, at least 30 minutes.
# Meanwhile, in a medium bowl, combine cream cheese, mayonnaise, and ranch dressing mix. Chill in refrigerator to blend flavors while crust cools.
# Spread the cream cheese mixture over the cooled crust. Top with broccoli, cauliflower, and carrots. Sprinkle with cheese and any additional vegetables, if using. Chill before cutting into squares.
# Recipe Notes
# ''To make Veggie Pizza ahead of time:''
# Bake the crust, cool completely, and cover with plastic wrap overnight.
# The cream cheese mixture can be made up to 1 day in advance.
# All vegetables can be prepped in advance too.
@@

@@.notes
* Any vegetable is pretty incredible on this pizza, but here are some other combos to light a spark or two for other delicious ideas. Be sure to cut the vegetables so they are bite-sized and are easier to eat. Finish with a dusting of shredded Parmesan cheese or some cracked pepper.
* Red peppers, black olives, and scallions with shredded mozzarella
* Chopped cherry tomatoes, crumbled bacon, cheddar cheese
* Chopped cucumbers, cherry tomatoes, crumbled feta cheese
* Tricolor peppers, carrots, and green onions
@@
